<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n30173d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n30" href="#n30173d">N30 (VI.B.22)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n30all.htm#n30173d"> 173(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> aberrant</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Nerve-impulses which arise in the skin should, of course, proceed to the centre for registering cutaneous sensations, but that centre is asleep, and the impulses failing to enter it are shunted into the visual centre where they become the physical basis of a dream. Such impulses we call &ldquo;<mark>aberrant</mark>&rdquo;, because they have wandered away from their own proper centre and reached the visual. <small> D. F. Fraser-Harris, <a name="FHMS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FHMS"><cite title="source">Morpheus, or: The Future of Sleep</cite></a> (1928) 54</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
